name: 3-cyanopyridine 1-oxide
Reason: The compound 3-cyanopyridine 1-oxide can be deconstructed into a pyridine ring as its basic unit and two functional groups: a cyano group (-C#N) and an N-oxide group (attached as [n+](o-)). The pyridine ring has a basic melting point comparable to that of pyridine itself, which is approximately 20 degrees Celsius. The presence of the cyano group generally increases the melting point due to the introduction of a strong dipole and potential for hydrogen bonding, which enhances intermolecular forces; this effect is estimated to contribute an increase of about +70 degrees Celsius. The N-oxide group adds another strong dipole to the molecule, and can also participate in hydrogen bonding, potentially increasing the melting point further; the influence of this could be approximated at +30 degrees Celsius. Therefore, the combined effect of these functional groups can be predicted to significantly increase the basic melting point of the pyridine ring.
